  <brief_title>The Role of Steroids Following Selective Laser Trabeculoplasty</brief_title>
  <official_title>The Role of Topical Prednisolone Acetate Following Selective Laser Trabeculoplasty</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>West Virginia University</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>West Virginia University</source>
  <oversight_info>
    <has_dmc>No</has_dmc>
  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      To evaluate whether or not using topical steroids after selective laser trabeculoplasty
      affects intraocular pressure outcomes.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      Subjects undergoing bilateral SLT will be randomly assigned to use prednisolone acetate 1% in
      one eye four times daily with no treatment in the fellow eye, for one week following SLT.
      Examinations will occur at baseline, and one week, one month and three months after SLT. IOP
      and anterior chamber inflammation will be noted at each visit.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
